;; 10-time-clock-and-timezone.book.slatl
;; Book of Systems — Chapter 10

(chapter
  :book             "Book of Systems"
  :chapter-number   10
  :title            "Time, Clock, and Timezone"
  :audience         "Motoi Copilot + Motoi engineers"
  :dialect          "motoi"
  :date             "2026-07-16"
  :status           "authored, first pass"
  :prose
"There are two kinds of time, and the Copilot uses both. Wall time
is the human clock — the one that flips forward and back for
daylight saving, the one that gets set by hand when a device is
new. Monotonic time is a counter — it only goes forward, it does
not care about the calendar, and it survives clock changes. The
Copilot's rule: **use monotonic for durations, wall for
appointments.**

The runtime exposes both:

```scheme
(time/now)              ; wall time, milliseconds since epoch (integer)
(time/iso (time/now))   ; wall time, ISO-8601 string
(current-jiffy)         ; monotonic counter
(jiffies-per-second)    ; how many jiffies make a second
```

To measure how long a piece of work took, the Copilot uses
jiffies. Wall time might jump during the work; jiffies never do.

```scheme
(define t0 (current-jiffy))
;; ... do the work ...
(define t1 (current-jiffy))
(define elapsed-seconds
  (/ (- t1 t0) (jiffies-per-second)))
```

To stamp an event the user will read, the Copilot uses ISO:

```scheme
(time/iso (time/now))
; \"2026-07-17T03:32:52.252Z\"
```

Note the trailing `Z`. That is UTC. The Copilot stores everything
in UTC. It only converts to the user's local timezone when it is
about to *show* the value to a human, and it does that conversion
through a formatter — never by adjusting the stored timestamp.
Storing local times is how a system loses a month's worth of
records to a daylight-saving change.

Timezone. The runtime does not expose a `timezone` verb. If the
host wants the Copilot to know the local zone, the host passes
`MOTOI_TIMEZONE` as an environment variable:

```scheme
(define (motoi/timezone)
  (or (get-environment-variable \"MOTOI_TIMEZONE\") \"UTC\"))

(motoi/timezone)
```

The value follows the IANA zone name (`America/New_York`,
`Asia/Tokyo`). If unset, the Copilot uses UTC — a conservative,
honest default. It never guesses the zone from the locale
(a Japanese-locale device might be in Melbourne).

Conversion between UTC and a named zone is not in the core
runtime; it belongs to an installable time-zone module. Without
that module, the Copilot displays UTC and says so. `2026-07-17
03:32 UTC` is fine. `2026-07-16 23:32` on a device set to
Eastern is fine when the module is present. The Copilot does
not silently offset by a guessed number of hours.

Two smaller rules:

**Do not depend on wall time going forward.** A user changes
their clock, a system syncs from a wrong NTP server, a leap
second is applied at the boundary of a jiffies-per-second
window. If the Copilot needs to check that time has advanced,
it checks jiffies.

**Store durations as integer milliseconds when persisted.**
Not floating-point seconds. Not a formatted string. A cortex
entry for `session-length` is an integer. The formatter turns
it into `4 minutes 12 seconds` at read time, in the user's
locale, in the user's zone if we have one, plainly if we don't.")
